John Edward: Language skills for world citizens essential
Scotland's independent schools continue to be distinguished by academic excellence. This continued in 2018 with further outstanding test results and is only supported by individual and joint successes in the fields of sports, art, music and other joint ventures.
With more than 30,000 students from all over Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the highest possible level of care for their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further education and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as a world citizen.
As an educational sector, which can shape and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and sought after in schools as elective subjects.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak to someone in a language he understands, you will reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart."
This is an impressive reminder that we cannot rely only on English if we want to build relations and trust with people from other countries.
The current audit results of this year show that languages with the highest existing rates are at the top of the rankings of independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of students who learned foreign languages obtained grade A at the higher examinations.
From the data collected from 74 SCIS member schools, 72 percent of the students in Mandarin achieved grade A at the higher examinations, while 72 percent of the students who learned German, 69 percent of the students who learned French, and 63 percent of the students who learned Spanish also achieved grade A.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as important knowledge that will undoubtedly need children and young people in the future.
Languages are today seen as elective subjects as well as STEM subjects (natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and other places.
According to a survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014, 17 percent of the reasons employers mentioned for the problems of the occupation of vacancies were related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary when it comes to preparing young people for their future career.
As more and more open jobs require languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the profession chosen, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage through such lifelong ability in the future.
Direct communication with people from other countries will automatically give multilingual people a head start before competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak any foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15 percent).
For this reason, it is important for the children of today that we now invest in language teaching.
Children who speak several languages, especially the languages of developing countries, will have a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught in all schools.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other languages will be taught, which will be considered by 2020 as the most important for the United Kingdom, for example Mandarin or Japanese.
Wherever your child’s interests lie, an independent school will always be able to choose a number of languages with appropriate specialised teachers.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares the children and equips them with the skills necessary for their success, whatever the future may be.
At this stage in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages remain of fundamental importance for the future of the country, which is why this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should actually be regarded as 'international communication capability'.
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
