The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital and is, in his opinion, the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to launch the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about it now, in my last year?’
After their words, no one had ever told her how important sleep is. That surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course for the first time this year explained to the students how the basics of good sleeping habits contribute to academic and sporting performance and also improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Managing Director of the University's Health Services, said that the University had decided to introduce the course after she found that students were under heavy sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In a section the students see the picture of a room in a home and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books. They get information about the effect of caffeine and light as well as the effects of lack of sleep on the sporting performance and the importance of a sleeping routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term withdrawal can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes and cancer.
Then, using a map of the university site, they are encouraged to think about their daily routine with interactive symbols.
“We know that it will not change students’ behaviour immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know this – just as you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health," said Professor Czeisler.
The pride of "moving a night shift" is still widespread, he said and added that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students made sleep shortage a growing problem.
Sufficient sleep should be the "secret weapon" of all students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said. Furthermore, weight gain could be avoided, since sleep deprivation puts the brain in starvation mode, so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course. Last year he finished one of his courses in Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and encouraged him to press on a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step all postgraduate students will be invited to undertake a similar study programme before taking up their studies at the competitive university.
