The opening ointments of the trade war between the USA and China were deafening. Although the battle is not over for a long time, Beijing could benefit from a long-term trench between the countries, my experts.
Donald Trump, the U.S. president, fired the first warning at the beginning of the year when he invested with criminal tariffs important Chinese exports, including solar cells, steel and aluminium.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new criminal tariffs on goods worth 200 billion dollars, effectively affecting half of all goods imported from China into the United States.
Beijing struck in the same way each time, and recently imposed fines of five to ten percent on American goods worth 60 billion dollars.
China vows to respond to any action by the US and it is unlikely that the world's second largest economic power will soon collapse.
Moving Washington to slow down would mean yielding. However, a public impact on the US would be far too defamatory for China’s President Xi Jinping.
Nevertheless, experts believe that if Beijing plays its cards well, China could benefit from the effects of the trade war in the long term by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"The fact that a rapid political decision could create the conditions for economic turbulence in both countries in Washington or Beijing is actually much more dangerous than many observers have previously recognized," says Abigail Grace, a scientific assistant who focuses on Asia at the Center for New American Security.
Syria is 'ready' to return refugees, according to the Minister for Foreign Affairs
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country that has been devastated by the seven-year war.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem explained that the situation in the country is improving.
"Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government is rebuilding the areas destroyed by terrorists in order to reverse normality.
All conditions were now given for the voluntary return of refugees to the country that they had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their everyday lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that over 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the start of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian government welcomes help in rebuilding the devastated country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept conditional assistance from countries that had supported the uprising.
Europe won the Ryder Cup in Paris
Team Europa won the 2018 Ryder Cup and defeated Team USA with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 in the Le Golf National near Paris.
The US has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won the Ryder Cup since 1993 in Europe.
Europe won back the crown after the team of the Danish captain Thomas Bjorn achieved the 14.5 points it needed to defeat the United States.
The American star Phil Mickelson, who had problems with much of the tournament, sank his fall on the 16th line (par 3) in the water and lost against Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all his rounds and became one of 4 players who scored a 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was beaten 5:4 by the player with the lowest ranking in the team Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
The player with the world's best ranking, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 to 1 against the Englishman Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
The Spaniard Sergio Garcia, veteran from eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player of all time with 25.5 career points.
“Normally I don’t cry, but today I couldn’t hold back.
It was a difficult year.
I am so grateful that Thomas chose me and believed in me.
I'm so infinitely happy to get the trophy back.
It is about the team and I am happy to have made a contribution," said the emotional Garcia after the European victory.
He passed the torch to his compatriot John Rahm, who won the singles against the American golf legend Tiger Woods on Sunday 2:1.
I'm so incredibly proud to have beaten Tiger Woods, who I've been following since my childhood on TV," says 23-year-old Rahm.
Woods lost all four games in France and now has a Ryder Cup balance of 13-21-3.
A strange statistic for one of the biggest players of all time who has won 14 important titles and is surpassed only by Jack Nicklaus.
The team USA had all weekend problems finding the fairways, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who performed high-quality performances throughout the tournament.
American captain Jim Furyk said after a disappointing performance of his team: “I am proud of the boys, they have fought.
There was a time this morning when we had put Europe under pressure.
We didn't do anything about it.
Take your hat off for Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All of his 12 players made a good performance.
We will regroup, I will talk to the PGA America and our Ryder Cup Committee and we will look forward.
I love these 12 guys and I'm proud to be their captain.
You have to pull the hat.
We were defeated."
Red Time Update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota are decreasing
The latest report of the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, in the areas of the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, more flowering conditions are recorded, indicating declining concentrations.
A red algae bloom extends over about 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinella to the south of the Lee district.
Sites can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough, but compared to the previous week in less places.
A red tide was also observed in the district of Pasco.
Last week, medium concentrations have been reported on or off the coast of Pinellas district, low to high concentrations off the coast of Manatee district, background to high concentrations on or off the coast of Charlotte district, background to high concentrations on or off the coast of Lee district and low concentrations in Collier district.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the districts of Pinella, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In the northwest of Florida, no new respiratory problems have been reported during the past week.
